ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Little cherry disease (LCD) is a serious problem for sweet and sour cherry producers in parts of northern Europe and North America. It can be caused by 2 closteroviruses, _Little cherry virus 1_ (LChV-1, not yet assigned to a genus) and LChV-2 (genus _Ampelovirus_), in single or mixed infections. Both viruses are present in North America, but the current outbreak in Washington appears to be associated with LChV-2 (see link below).

Symptoms vary with host cultivars, but may include reduced size and quality of fruit, premature leaf reddening, stunting of seedlings, and some loss of tree vigour. All commercial cherry cultivars are susceptible, and ornamental flowering cherries can be asymptomatic reservoirs of LChV-1.

LChV-2 is transmitted by one or several species of mealybug vectors which can be spread by wind and with packing material in their nymph stages. An insect vector for LChV-1 is not known. Both viruses can be spread by both shoot and root grafting and with infected plant material. Disease management for LCD includes use of certified clean planting stock and budwood, elimination of inoculum (removal of infected trees, as mentioned above), and vector control for LChV-2.

